Data¶

System Data¶

Where do Citi Bikers ride? When do they ride? How far do they go? Which stations are most popular? What days of the week are most rides taken on? We've heard all of these questions and more from you, and we're happy to provide the data to help you discover the answers to these questions and more. We invite developers, engineers, statisticians, artists, academics and other interested members of the public to use the data we provide for analysis, development, visualization and whatever else moves you. (text, dataset from: https://ride.citibikenyc.com/system-data)

Data analyzed in this notebook: https://s3.amazonaws.com/tripdata/201406-citibike-tripdata.zip

  • Note: unarchive data and save csv file into input_data\2014-06_citi_bike_trip_data.csv

When do they ride?¶

The following graph shows how hours are exposed during a day. Timestamps are streamlined to hours of ride start or end.

This does not represent the average count of how many bikes are ridden in any given hour, but the usual times of beginnings and ends of rides.

In [2]:
data["starthour"] = data["startdatetime"].dt.hour
data["stophour"]  = data["stopdatetime"].dt.hour

df = pd.DataFrame({"Start Hour":data.groupby(["starthour"]).size(), "Stop Hour":data.groupby(["stophour"]).size()})

pl = df.plot(legend=True,kind="line", figsize=PLOT_SIZE)
pl.set(xlabel="Hour", ylabel="No. of drives", title="When do they ride?")

How far do Citi Bikers go?¶

The following graph shows the histogram of all rides distances with a resolution of 100m.

Ride distance is computed as the great circle distance between the start and end station.

In [5]:
from geopy.distance import great_circle

HIST_RESOLUTION = 100 #meters

def get_distance(lat1:float, lon1:float, lat2:float, lon2:float) -> float:
    """Calculate great circle distance between two points.
    
    Args:
        lat1(float): Point 1 latitude.
        lon1(float): Point 1 longitude.
        lat2(float): Point 2 latitude.
        lon2(float): Point 2 longitude.
    """
    coordinates_from = (lat1, lon1)
    coordinates_to   = (lat2, lon2)
    return great_circle(coordinates_from, coordinates_to).meters

data["distance"] = data[["start_station_latitude", "start_station_longitude","end_station_latitude", "end_station_longitude"]].apply(lambda x: get_distance(*x), axis=1)

data.hist(column="distance", bins=int(data["distance"].max()/HIST_RESOLUTION), figsize=PLOT_SIZE)
Out[5]:
array([[<AxesSubplot:title={'center':'distance'}>]], dtype=object)

Where do Citi Bikers ride?¶

The plot show location of station in NYC visited by Citi Bikers, size of the circle represents number of visits this month. Darker color indicates that stations are lovated nearby (circles overlaps).

Blue lines on map background are cycle roads.

Map source: https://www.openstreetmap.org/#map=12/40.7115/-74.0341&layers=C

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.image as mpimg

df               = pd.DataFrame()
df               = data.groupby(["start_station_name"]).size() + data.groupby(["end_station_name"]).size()
stations         = df.sort_values(ascending=False)

stations         = stations.reset_index()
#rename 2 columns from groupby selection
stations.columns = ["station_name", "visits"]
#prepare list of columns to be droped after concatenate dataframes
columns_to_rem   = list(data.columns)
columns_to_rem.remove("start_station_latitude")
columns_to_rem.remove("start_station_longitude")
#concatenate dataframes, drop unused columns, drop start_station_ prefix
stations         = pd.concat([stations, data.reindex(stations.index)], axis=1)
stations         = stations.drop(columns=columns_to_rem)
stations.columns = stations.columns.str.replace("start_station_", "")

print(stations)

nyc_image        = mpimg.imread("nyc.png")

stations.plot(kind="scatter", x="longitude", y="latitude",
    s=stations["visits"]/50, label="Station visits", alpha=0.5, figsize=PLOT_SIZE,
)
plt.imshow(nyc_image, extent=[-74.0643, -73.8991, 40.6739, 40.7844], alpha=0.5)
plt.legend()
plt.show()
